video_description: This is the most dangerous city in the United States.   It’s Bessemer, Alabama, found just west of Birmingham, and it has a violent crime rate of 33 per 1,000 residents, almost nine times more than the national average.  The town has a population of 26,000 and presents a blend of everyday life, but it also is home to an eerie abundance of abandoned structures, ranging from historic residences to shopping malls and even football fields. But the town does boast some culinary gems like Bright Star, the oldest restaurant in Alabama serving up renowned snapper and gumbo.  Additionally, Bessemer marks the birthplace of several notable figures. Heisman winner Jameis Winston is from here along with perhaps the most athletically gifted professional athlete of all time, Bo Jackson. video_description: CNN's Elizabeth Wagmeister interviews Gypsy Rose Blanchard, who was released from prison after serving eight years over a plot to kill her abusive mother, Dee Dee Blanchard. She pleaded guilty to second-degree murder in 2016 and admitted that she convinced her then-boyfriend to stab her mother to death. Blanchard was a victim of Munchausen syndrome by proxy, a rare disorder in which a caregiver feigns or exaggerates illness in someone to elicit attention or sympathy. She had spent her childhood and early adulthood believing she suffered from a host of serious ailments, including leukemia, muscular dystrophy and asthma. After the abuse she experienced at the hands of her mother came to light, Blanchard was sentenced to 10 years in prison and released two years early on December 28th. According to the Missouri Department of Corrections, she is expected to remain under parole supervision until June 2025. #cnn
